{"query_id":"q001","question":"What are the most common signs and symptoms of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Common signs and symptoms of colorectal cancer include rectal bleeding, blood in the stool, changes in bowel habits, abdominal pain or cramping, feeling that the bowel does not empty completely, decreased appetite, weight loss, and anemia."}
{"query_id":"q002","question":"At what age should average-risk adults start colorectal cancer screening?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Average-risk adults should begin regular colorectal cancer screening at age 45."}
{"query_id":"q003","question":"Which screening tests are recommended for colorectal cancer detection?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Recommended colorectal cancer screening tests include FIT every year, gFOBT every year, stool DNA tests every 3 years, colonoscopy every 10 years, CT colonography every 5 years, and sigmoidoscopy every 5 years."}
{"query_id":"q004","question":"What lifestyle factors increase the risk of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risk factors include excess body weight, physical inactivity, smoking, high consumption of red or processed meat, low calcium intake, low intake of fruits and vegetables, and heavy alcohol consumption."}
{"query_id":"q005","question":"How can colorectal cancer be prevented?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Regular screening, maintaining a healthy diet, staying physically active, keeping a healthy weight, and avoiding alcohol and tobacco can help reduce colorectal cancer risk."}
{"query_id":"q006","question":"What are the main treatment options for colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Treatment options may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiation therapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy depending on tumor stage and patient condition."}
{"query_id":"q007","question":"What foods are recommended before bowel cancer surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Before surgery, patients are encouraged to eat protein-rich foods such as chicken, fish, eggs, lentils, tofu, beans, nuts, and seeds, along with fibre-rich carbohydrates like wholegrain bread, rice, and pasta."}
{"query_id":"q008","question":"How can patients manage low appetite during bowel cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients can try eating smaller meals more often, using high-calorie drinks, eating plain foods, and avoiding strong-smelling or spicy foods."}
{"query_id":"q009","question":"Why is fibre important for bowel health?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Fibre helps food move through the bowel, supports healthy gut bacteria, prevents constipation, and helps control weight and appetite."}
{"query_id":"q010","question":"What are examples of soluble fibre foods?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Examples of soluble fibre foods include oats, barley, beans, peas, lentils, chickpeas, fruits, and vegetables."}
{"query_id":"q011","question":"What advice is given for following a low-fibre diet?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients on a low-fibre diet may eat peeled fruits, cooked low-fibre vegetables, seedless fruits, and foods with soluble fibre while avoiding skins and seeds."}
{"query_id":"q012","question":"How much red meat is recommended per week for bowel cancer prevention?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People are advised to eat no more than three portions of red meat per week, around 350g to 500g cooked meat."}
{"query_id":"q013","question":"Why should processed meat be avoided?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Processed meats such as bacon, sausages, ham, and salami may increase the risk of bowel cancer."}
{"query_id":"q014","question":"What are common causes of weight loss in bowel cancer patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Weight loss may be caused by the cancer itself, treatment side effects, appetite loss, diarrhoea, constipation, fatigue, nausea, or problems absorbing nutrients."}
{"query_id":"q015","question":"What strategies can help patients cope with cancer-related fatigue?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Helpful strategies include eating small frequent meals, staying hydrated, preparing meals in advance, asking for help with cooking, and maintaining light physical activity."}
{"query_id":"q016","question":"What dietary advice is recommended for people with a stoma?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a stoma are advised to eat a balanced diet, drink plenty of fluids, chew food well, and eat smaller meals while monitoring foods that trigger symptoms."}
{"query_id":"q017","question":"What is ctDNA testing and how is it used in colon cancer management?","language":"en","reference_answer":"ctDNA (circulating tumor DNA), also called a liquid biopsy, looks for small pieces of DNA released by tumor cells into the blood. It can help detect cancer, monitor treatment response, and check for recurrence."}
{"query_id":"q018","question":"What surveillance is recommended for stage 1 colon cancer after treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Stage 1 colon cancer surveillance includes colonoscopy at 1 year after treatment, then every 3 to 5 years if no abnormalities are found."}
{"query_id":"q019","question":"What is low anterior resection syndrome (LARS) and what causes it?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Low anterior resection syndrome is a set of long-term bowel problems that can occur after rectal cancer surgery including frequent bowel movements, urgency, incontinence, and difficulty emptying the bowel."}
{"query_id":"q020","question":"What biomarkers should be tested in metastatic colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Metastatic colon cancers should be tested for dMMR/MSI-H, RAS and BRAF mutations, HER2 amplification, NTRK fusion, and POLE/POLD1 mutations to guide treatment decisions."}
{"query_id":"q021","question":"What does mismatch repair deficiency (dMMR) mean and why does it matter for treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"dMMR (mismatch repair deficiency) or MSI-H means the cancer has defects in DNA repair genes. These cancers may respond well to immunotherapy such as pembrolizumab."}
{"query_id":"q022","question":"What are the phases of clinical trials and what does each phase test?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Phase 1 trials test safety and side effects of a new treatment. Phase 2 trials assess whether the treatment works. Phase 3 trials compare the new treatment against standard treatments in a larger group."}
{"query_id":"q023","question":"What is chemotherapy-induced neuropathy and how can it be managed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Chemotherapy-induced neuropathy is nerve damage caused by chemotherapy that results in pain, numbness, tingling, swelling, or muscle weakness. Patients should ask their care team about prevention and management options."}
{"query_id":"q024","question":"How long after stoma formation is stoma reversal surgery typically performed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"It is possible to have a stoma reversal two to four months after stoma formation, but it is more likely to be performed six to twelve months later depending on recovery and whether further treatment such as chemotherapy is needed."}
{"query_id":"q025","question":"What bowel changes should patients expect after stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After stoma reversal, the bowel is likely to work differently due to the missing section of bowel. Patients may experience frequent loose stools, urgency, or difficulty controlling bowel movements, which usually improve over time."}
{"query_id":"q026","question":"What diet is recommended after stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After stoma reversal, patients should eat little and often rather than large meals, avoid rich or spicy foods initially, drink plenty of fluids, and gradually reintroduce foods to identify triggers."}
{"query_id":"q027","question":"What are the possible risks of having a colonic stent fitted?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risks include stent failure, bowel perforation, stent migration, re-obstruction from tumour growth through the stent mesh, bleeding, and mild discomfort or pain."}
{"query_id":"q028","question":"What symptoms after colonic stenting should prompt urgent contact with a specialist nurse?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should contact their specialist nurse immediately if they experience more than mild abdominal pain or tenderness, heavy bleeding from the bottom, fever or rapid heart rate, or worsening constipation, nausea, or bloating."}
{"query_id":"q029","question":"What diet is recommended in the days after a colonic stent is fitted?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should start with liquids only, then gradually introduce soft foods such as porridge, smoothies, well-cooked casseroles and soups, avoiding hard foods like raw vegetables, nuts, and seeds."}
{"query_id":"q030","question":"What is the recommended method for collecting a urine specimen from a urostomy stoma?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The recommended method is sterile catheterization of the urostomy stoma. If a catheter is unavailable, a clean-catch specimen can be collected directly from the stoma after removing the pouch and cleansing the stoma."}
{"query_id":"q031","question":"What should clinicians consider before giving antibiotics for urinary infection in urostomy patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Antibiotics should be used with caution; patients should only be treated for symptomatic infections such as fever, flank pain, or new-onset cloudy urine with odour. Asymptomatic bacteriuria in urostomy patients should not be treated with antibiotics."}
{"query_id":"q032","question":"What is the normal daily urinary output range to monitor after urostomy surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Normal urinary output is defined as 800 to 1200 mL per day. Monitoring output helps detect complications such as dehydration, obstruction, or anastomotic leaks."}
{"query_id":"q033","question":"What early postoperative complications should nurses watch for after urostomy surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Early complications include stomal necrosis, mucocutaneous separation, retraction, prolapse, and peristomal skin breakdown. These should be reported to the surgical team promptly."}
{"query_id":"q034","question":"Can people with a urostomy go swimming, and what precautions are recommended?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Swimming with a secure pouch is fine. Before swimming, the pouch should be emptied and secured in place with waterproof tape if needed."}
{"query_id":"q035","question":"What are the main symptoms of bowel cancer that patients should watch for?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Symptoms of bowel cancer include bleeding from the bottom, blood in the stool, a change in bowel habits lasting more than three weeks, unexplained weight loss, and unexplained tiredness."}
{"query_id":"q036","question":"At what age is bowel cancer screening offered in England, Scotland, and Wales?","language":"en","reference_answer":"In England, Scotland, and Wales, people are invited to take part in bowel cancer screening starting at age 50. In Northern Ireland, the screening age differs."}
{"query_id":"q037","question":"What legal workplace protections apply when a person is diagnosed with cancer in the UK?","language":"en","reference_answer":"From the date of diagnosis, cancer patients are protected from discrimination at work under the Equality Act 2010 in England, Scotland, and Wales, or the Disability Discrimination Act in Northern Ireland. Employers must make reasonable adjustments."}
{"query_id":"q038","question":"Can people with a stoma travel by plane, and what documents help at airport security?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Yes, people with a stoma can travel by plane. A travel certificate from the stoma care nurse specialist can help at security to explain the stoma and related supplies, and is especially useful for international travel."}
{"query_id":"q039","question":"What are the different types of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The most common type is adenocarcinoma, which develops from the cells lining the inner wall of the colon or rectum. Less common types include carcinoid tumours, gastrointestinal stromal tumours, lymphomas, and sarcomas."}
{"query_id":"q040","question":"Which hereditary syndromes increase the risk of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Hereditary syndromes that increase colorectal cancer risk include Lynch syndrome (hereditary non-polyposis colorectal cancer) and familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP). People with these syndromes should begin screening at a younger age."}
{"query_id":"q041","question":"What quality of life issues do colorectal cancer survivors commonly experience?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colorectal cancer survivors may experience lasting side effects from treatment including bowel changes, fatigue, sexual dysfunction, emotional distress, and concerns about cancer recurrence. Survivorship care plans and support services can help address these issues."}
{"query_id":"q042","question":"What are the survival statistics for colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colorectal cancer survival depends strongly on the stage at diagnosis. Early-stage cancers have much higher survival rates than advanced-stage cancers. Overall, around 65% of people diagnosed with colorectal cancer survive 5 years or more."}
{"query_id":"q043","question":"What pelvic floor exercises are recommended after stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Pelvic floor exercises help strengthen the muscles controlling the bowel and bladder after reversal surgery. Patients are advised to squeeze and hold the pelvic floor muscles regularly throughout the day, especially to reduce urgency and improve continence."}
{"query_id":"q044","question":"What are the surgical risks of stoma reversal?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risks of stoma reversal surgery include anastomotic leak, infection, bleeding, bowel obstruction, and the need for a further stoma. Some of these complications can be serious and may require additional surgery."}
{"query_id":"q045","question":"What physical restrictions should patients follow after stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After stoma reversal, patients should avoid heavy lifting and strenuous activity for several weeks, gradually returning to normal activities as advised by their surgical team. Driving is usually restricted until they can make an emergency stop comfortably."}
{"query_id":"q046","question":"What emotional impact can having a stoma have and how can patients cope?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A stoma can affect a person's body image, self-confidence, and emotional wellbeing. Patients may feel anxious, low, or embarrassed. Talking to a stoma nurse, counsellor, or peer support group can help with emotional adjustment."}
{"query_id":"q047","question":"When can patients resume sexual activity after stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Most patients can resume sexual activity once they feel comfortable, usually after around six weeks. Patients should discuss any concerns about sexual function or intimacy with their clinical team."}
{"query_id":"q048","question":"What is a colonic stent and why is it used?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A colonic stent is a small metal mesh tube placed inside the bowel to hold it open when it has become blocked by a tumour. It is used to relieve bowel obstruction either as a bridge to surgery or as a palliative treatment."}
{"query_id":"q049","question":"How long does the colonic stent fitting procedure take?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The colonic stent procedure typically takes around 30 to 60 minutes and is performed under sedation or local anaesthetic using an endoscope and X-ray guidance."}
{"query_id":"q050","question":"How might bowel habits change after a colonic stent is fitted?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After a stent is fitted, patients may notice looser or more frequent stools than usual. It can take a few days for the bowel to settle and for patients to return to a more regular pattern."}
{"query_id":"q051","question":"What are the alternatives to colonic stenting for bowel obstruction?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Alternatives to colonic stenting include emergency surgery to remove or bypass the blockage, which may result in a temporary or permanent stoma, or palliative treatment without surgical intervention for patients who are not fit for surgery."}
{"query_id":"q052","question":"What are the key principles of a balanced diet for bowel cancer patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A balanced diet includes a variety of fruits and vegetables, starchy carbohydrates, protein foods such as fish, poultry, legumes, and dairy, while limiting red meat, processed food, alcohol, and foods high in saturated fat and sugar."}
{"query_id":"q053","question":"What role does protein play in recovery from bowel cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Protein is essential for repairing tissue, supporting the immune system, and maintaining muscle mass during and after treatment. Good sources include lean meats, fish, eggs, dairy, legumes, tofu, and nuts."}
{"query_id":"q054","question":"Which foods are most likely to cause wind or gas with a stoma?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Foods that commonly cause gas include beans, lentils, onions, garlic, cabbage, broccoli, fizzy drinks, beer, and chewing gum. Patients can try reducing these foods to manage wind."}
{"query_id":"q055","question":"What dietary changes help manage constipation after bowel cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"To manage constipation, patients should increase fluid intake, eat more fibre-rich foods such as fruit, vegetables, and wholegrains, and stay physically active. Laxatives may also be recommended by a healthcare professional."}
{"query_id":"q056","question":"What dietary advice helps manage diarrhoea after bowel cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For diarrhoea, patients are advised to drink plenty of fluids to prevent dehydration, eat small and frequent meals, avoid high-fat, spicy, or very sweet foods, and try eating foods that can help firm up stools such as bananas, white rice, and toast."}
{"query_id":"q057","question":"What dietary advice is given specifically for people with a colostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a colostomy should eat regular balanced meals, chew food thoroughly, drink adequate fluids, and identify foods that affect their stoma output. Some people may need to avoid certain foods that cause blockages or excess output."}
{"query_id":"q058","question":"What dietary advice is given specifically for people with an ileostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with an ileostomy need to drink extra fluids and replace electrolytes lost through the stoma, eat small frequent meals, chew food well, and be cautious with high-fibre foods that may cause blockages. Salt and potassium intake may need to be increased."}
{"query_id":"q059","question":"How can bowel cancer patients gain weight if they are losing too much?","language":"en","reference_answer":"To gain weight, patients can eat more frequently, choose calorie-dense foods such as full-fat dairy, nut butters, and avocado, add healthy fats and proteins to meals, use oral nutritional supplements if recommended, and seek support from a dietitian."}
{"query_id":"q060","question":"Are vitamin and mineral supplements recommended for bowel cancer patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Supplements should only be taken on the advice of a healthcare professional. Some patients may need specific supplements such as vitamin D, iron, vitamin B12, or calcium depending on their treatment and dietary intake. A balanced diet remains the best source of nutrients."}
{"query_id":"q061","question":"What dietary habits may help reduce the risk of bowel cancer recurrence?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After treatment, eating a diet rich in fruit, vegetables, wholegrains, and legumes, maintaining a healthy weight, limiting red and processed meat, avoiding alcohol, and staying physically active may help reduce the risk of recurrence."}
{"query_id":"q062","question":"What reasonable adjustments can employers make for employees returning to work after cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Reasonable adjustments may include flexible working hours, reduced hours or phased return, working from home, changing duties to avoid physical strain, providing rest breaks, and adapting the workplace to accommodate any lasting effects of treatment."}
{"query_id":"q063","question":"What financial benefits may be available to people with bowel cancer in the UK?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with cancer may be entitled to benefits including Personal Independence Payment (PIP), Employment and Support Allowance (ESA), Universal Credit, Attendance Allowance, and Carer's Allowance for their carers. A welfare benefits advisor can help identify entitlements."}
{"query_id":"q064","question":"Are cancer patients entitled to free prescriptions in the UK?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Yes, people with cancer are entitled to free NHS prescriptions in England if they have a medical exemption certificate. Prescriptions are already free in Wales, Scotland, and Northern Ireland regardless of diagnosis."}
{"query_id":"q065","question":"Can bowel cancer patients apply for a Blue Badge parking permit?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Some bowel cancer patients may qualify for a Blue Badge if their condition significantly affects their ability to walk or if they are in severe pain when moving. The application is assessed individually and a diagnosis of cancer alone does not automatically qualify someone."}
{"query_id":"q066","question":"What help is available with transport costs for cancer patients in the UK?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Cancer patients may be able to get help with travel costs to hospital through the NHS Healthcare Travel Costs Scheme if they are receiving certain benefits. Some charities also offer transport assistance for cancer patients."}
{"query_id":"q067","question":"What travel insurance considerations are there for stoma patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Stoma patients should declare their condition when purchasing travel insurance. It is important to find a policy that covers pre-existing conditions. Patients should carry enough supplies for the trip plus extra, and consider taking a letter from their stoma nurse when travelling internationally."}
{"query_id":"q068","question":"How does the large bowel work normally?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The large bowel, or colon, absorbs water and salts from undigested food, turning liquid waste from the small intestine into solid stools. Stools are stored in the rectum and passed out through the anus when the person is ready to open their bowels."}
{"query_id":"q069","question":"What factors are known to increase the risk of bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risk factors for bowel cancer include age over 50, a family history of bowel cancer, a personal history of polyps, inflammatory bowel disease, a diet high in red or processed meat, excess weight, physical inactivity, alcohol consumption, and smoking."}
{"query_id":"q070","question":"Why does early detection of bowel cancer matter?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel cancer found at an early stage is much more likely to be successfully treated. Many people with early bowel cancer have no symptoms, which is why screening is important to detect the cancer or pre-cancerous polyps before symptoms develop."}
{"query_id":"q071","question":"How frequently should people participate in bowel cancer screening?","language":"en","reference_answer":"In the UK, people aged 50 to 74 are offered a home bowel cancer screening test every two years. Those with higher risk due to family history or other factors may be offered more frequent or earlier surveillance such as colonoscopy."}
{"query_id":"q072","question":"What are colorectal polyps and how do they become cancerous?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colorectal polyps are growths on the inner lining of the colon or rectum. Most polyps are benign, but some types, especially adenomas, can gradually develop into cancer over a period of years if not removed. Regular colonoscopy allows polyps to be detected and removed before this happens."}
{"query_id":"q073","question":"How is colorectal cancer staged using the TNM system?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The TNM system stages colorectal cancer by tumour size and local invasion (T), lymph node involvement (N), and distant metastasis (M). Stages range from stage I (localised) through stage IV (metastatic). Staging guides treatment decisions and prognosis."}
{"query_id":"q074","question":"What is DPYD deficiency and why does it matter before starting chemotherapy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"DPYD deficiency is a genetic condition affecting the enzyme that breaks down fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy drugs such as 5-FU and capecitabine. Patients with DPYD variants may experience severe or life-threatening toxicity at standard doses. Testing before treatment allows dose adjustments to be made."}
{"query_id":"q075","question":"What fertility preservation options should be discussed before colorectal cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Before treatment, patients of reproductive age should discuss fertility preservation options with their oncologist. For women this may include egg or embryo freezing. For men, sperm banking is an option. Some treatments can impair fertility permanently, so early referral to a fertility specialist is important."}
{"query_id":"q076","question":"What is a colectomy and when is it recommended for colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A colectomy is the surgical removal of part or all of the colon. It is the primary treatment for most non-metastatic colon cancers. The extent of surgery depends on the tumour location, stage, and whether lymph nodes need to be removed. A partial colectomy removes the affected segment; a total colectomy removes the entire colon."}
{"query_id":"q077","question":"What adjuvant chemotherapy is recommended after surgery for stage III colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Stage III colon cancer is typically treated with adjuvant chemotherapy after surgery to reduce the risk of recurrence. FOLFOX (folinic acid, fluorouracil, oxaliplatin) or CAPOX (capecitabine plus oxaliplatin) are the standard regimens, usually given for six months."}
{"query_id":"q078","question":"What surveillance is recommended after treatment for stage I colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After curative treatment for stage I colon cancer, surveillance typically includes colonoscopy at one year, then every three to five years if clear. Regular clinical follow-up visits and imaging may also be recommended depending on individual circumstances."}
{"query_id":"q079","question":"What are the treatment options for liver metastases from colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For liver metastases from colon cancer, treatment options include surgical resection of metastases, ablation techniques (radiofrequency or microwave), hepatic arterial infusion chemotherapy, stereotactic body radiation, and systemic chemotherapy with or without targeted agents. The goal may be curative or to control disease."}
{"query_id":"q080","question":"What is the difference between supportive care and palliative care in cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Supportive care addresses symptoms and side effects of cancer and its treatment at any stage of disease. Palliative care focuses on comfort and quality of life when cancer cannot be cured, but it can be given alongside active treatment. Both aim to improve wellbeing but are not the same as end-of-life care."}
{"query_id":"q081","question":"What is hepatic arterial infusion chemotherapy and when is it used?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Hepatic arterial infusion (HAI) chemotherapy delivers chemotherapy directly into the hepatic artery to target liver metastases with a higher local drug concentration. It may be used for liver-only or liver-dominant colorectal cancer that is not resectable or has not responded to systemic therapy."}
{"query_id":"q082","question":"What are the standard first-line chemotherapy regimens for metastatic colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Standard first-line regimens for metastatic colon cancer include FOLFOX (folinic acid, fluorouracil, oxaliplatin), FOLFIRI (folinic acid, fluorouracil, irinotecan), and CAPOX. These may be combined with targeted agents such as bevacizumab (anti-VEGF) or cetuximab or panitumumab (anti-EGFR, for RAS wild-type tumours)."}
{"query_id":"q083","question":"What bowel changes can occur after colon surgery and how long do they last?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After colon surgery, patients may have looser stools, more frequent bowel movements, urgency, or difficulty controlling the bowel. These changes often improve gradually over weeks to months as the bowel adapts. Diet, pelvic floor exercises, and medications can help manage symptoms."}
{"query_id":"q084","question":"How can patients manage chemotherapy-induced peripheral neuropathy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Management of chemotherapy-induced peripheral neuropathy may include dose reduction or changing the chemotherapy regimen, medications for nerve pain such as duloxetine, physical therapy, and safety measures to prevent falls or burns due to reduced sensation. Patients should report new or worsening symptoms to their care team."}
{"query_id":"q085","question":"What is financial toxicity in cancer care and how can patients get help?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Financial toxicity refers to the financial hardship that cancer treatment costs can cause, including out-of-pocket expenses, lost income, and debt. Patients can seek help from hospital social workers, financial counsellors, patient assistance programs, and charitable organisations to reduce the financial burden of cancer care."}
{"query_id":"q086","question":"What is a low glycaemic load diet and how might it benefit colorectal cancer survivors?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A low glycaemic load diet emphasises foods that do not cause rapid spikes in blood sugar, such as wholegrains, legumes, non-starchy vegetables, and lean proteins, while limiting refined carbohydrates and sugary foods. Some evidence suggests this eating pattern may support healthy weight and reduce cancer recurrence risk."}
{"query_id":"q087","question":"Which immunotherapy drugs are used for dMMR metastatic colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For dMMR (mismatch repair deficient) or MSI-H metastatic colon cancer, immune checkpoint inhibitors such as pembrolizumab (Keytruda) and nivolumab (Opdivo), with or without ipilimumab, are approved treatments. dMMR tumours tend to respond particularly well to immunotherapy."}
{"query_id":"q088","question":"How often should a urostomy pouch be changed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A urostomy pouch should typically be changed every one to three days, or whenever it becomes full or begins to leak. Drainable pouches should be emptied regularly before they become more than half full. The exact frequency depends on the individual's output and the type of pouch used."}
{"query_id":"q089","question":"What is the best time of day to change a urostomy pouch?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The best time to change a urostomy pouch is in the morning before drinking fluids, when urine output is at its lowest. This makes the change easier and reduces the chance of urine flowing during the procedure."}
{"query_id":"q090","question":"How can urostomy surgery affect sexual function?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Urostomy surgery involving the bladder or surrounding structures can affect nerves and blood vessels involved in sexual function. Men may experience erectile dysfunction or dry orgasm; women may notice vaginal dryness or reduced sensation. Patients should discuss these concerns with their healthcare team as support and treatments are available."}
{"query_id":"q091","question":"What are the step-by-step instructions for changing a urostomy pouching system?","language":"en","reference_answer":"To change a urostomy pouch, gather supplies, wash hands, remove the old pouch by gently peeling the adhesive, clean the stoma and skin with warm water, dry the area thoroughly, measure the stoma, cut the new pouch to fit, apply any protective accessories, and press the new pouch firmly in place to seal."}
{"query_id":"q092","question":"What support groups are available for urostomy patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Urostomy patients can access support through organisations such as the Urostomy Association, UOAA (United Ostomy Associations of America), and local ostomy support groups. These provide peer support, education, and resources to help people adjust to living with a urostomy."}
{"query_id":"q093","question":"Why is preoperative nurse education important for patients undergoing urostomy surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Preoperative education by a specialist ostomy nurse helps patients understand the procedure, what the stoma will look like, and how to care for it. It also allows stoma siting to be done before surgery and reduces anxiety, which is associated with better outcomes and faster recovery."}
{"query_id":"q094","question":"Why should urine not be collected directly from an existing urostomy pouch for culture?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Urine collected from an existing pouch becomes contaminated with bacteria that colonise the pouch over time. This results in false-positive cultures and inappropriate antibiotic use. A freshly obtained specimen via catheterization or clean-catch provides an accurate result."}
{"query_id":"q095","question":"How should a clean-catch urine specimen be collected from a urostomy stoma?","language":"en","reference_answer":"To collect a clean-catch specimen, remove the pouch, clean the stoma with sterile gauze, allow a small amount of urine to flow and discard it, then collect the mid-stream specimen directly into a sterile container, taking care not to touch the stoma with the container."}
{"query_id":"q096","question":"What are the signs and symptoms of a urinary tract infection in a urostomy patient?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Signs of UTI in urostomy patients include fever, flank or back pain, new-onset cloudy or foul-smelling urine, increased output, nausea, and general malaise. Asymptomatic bacteriuria without these symptoms should not routinely be treated."}
{"query_id":"q097","question":"How long can a urine specimen be stored at room temperature before it must be processed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A urine specimen should ideally be processed within two hours of collection. If it cannot be processed immediately, it should be refrigerated at 4 degrees Celsius and processed within 24 hours to prevent bacterial overgrowth and inaccurate results."}
{"query_id":"q098","question":"What special considerations apply when collecting urine from a urostomy that has stents in place?","language":"en","reference_answer":"When ureteral stents are present in a urostomy, catheterization should be done carefully to avoid displacing the stents. The procedure requires specialist knowledge and should be performed by a trained nurse or clinician. The specimen should be labelled to indicate stent presence as this affects interpretation."}
{"query_id":"q099","question":"When should colorectal cancer screening begin for people at average risk?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For average-risk adults, colorectal cancer screening should begin at age 45. Screening before age 45 may be recommended for people with a family history of colorectal cancer or certain hereditary conditions."}
{"query_id":"q100","question":"What colorectal cancer screening tests are available and how do they differ?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Available colorectal cancer screening tests include stool-based tests (FIT, gFOBT, stool DNA) that are non-invasive and done at home, and structural exams (colonoscopy, CT colonography, sigmoidoscopy) that directly view the colon. Stool tests need to be done more frequently; colonoscopy provides the most complete examination and allows polyp removal."}
{"query_id":"q101","question":"What screening is recommended for people at high risk of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"High-risk individuals, including those with a family history of colorectal cancer, a personal history of adenomatous polyps, inflammatory bowel disease, or hereditary syndromes such as Lynch syndrome or FAP, should begin screening earlier and more frequently, typically with colonoscopy every one to five years depending on the level of risk."}
{"query_id":"q102","question":"What are the benefits of regular colorectal cancer screening?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Regular screening can detect colorectal cancer at an early and more treatable stage, remove precancerous polyps before they become cancer, and reduce colorectal cancer mortality. Screening is especially effective because colorectal cancer often has no symptoms in its early stages."}
{"query_id":"q103","question":"What is the first-line treatment approach for metastatic colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"First-line treatment for metastatic colorectal cancer typically involves combination chemotherapy such as FOLFOX or FOLFIRI, often combined with a targeted agent such as bevacizumab or, for RAS wild-type tumours, an anti-EGFR antibody such as cetuximab or panitumumab. The choice depends on tumour biomarkers and patient fitness."}
{"query_id":"q104","question":"What is the role of bevacizumab in treating metastatic colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bevacizumab is an anti-VEGF monoclonal antibody that inhibits tumour blood vessel growth (angiogenesis). It is used in combination with chemotherapy for first and second-line treatment of metastatic colorectal cancer and has been shown to improve progression-free survival."}
{"query_id":"q105","question":"What treatment options are available when first-line therapy fails in metastatic colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Second-line options after first-line failure in metastatic colorectal cancer depend on what was used initially. If FOLFOX was given first, FOLFIRI plus a biologic agent may be used second-line. Other options include ramucirumab, aflibercept, regorafenib, trifluridine/tipiracil, and encorafenib plus cetuximab for BRAF V600E mutant tumours."}
{"query_id":"q106","question":"Why is RAS mutation testing important in metastatic colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"RAS mutations (KRAS and NRAS) predict lack of response to anti-EGFR therapies such as cetuximab and panitumumab. Only patients with RAS wild-type tumours benefit from these agents. Testing is therefore essential before choosing a biologic agent to ensure appropriate treatment selection."}
{"query_id":"q107","question":"What staging workup is recommended for newly diagnosed colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Staging workup typically includes CT scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis, colonoscopy with biopsy, CEA blood test, and for rectal cancer, MRI of the pelvis. PET scan may be used in selected cases. Pathological staging is confirmed after surgical resection."}
{"query_id":"q108","question":"What is the recommended treatment for stage II colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Stage II colon cancer is primarily treated with surgical resection. Adjuvant chemotherapy may be considered for high-risk stage II tumours such as those with T4 staging, bowel perforation, inadequate lymph node sampling, high-grade histology, or perineural/lymphovascular invasion."}
{"query_id":"q109","question":"What perioperative chemotherapy is recommended for locally advanced rectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For locally advanced rectal cancer, neoadjuvant treatment before surgery is standard. Options include short-course radiotherapy, long-course chemoradiation, or total neoadjuvant therapy (combining chemotherapy and radiotherapy before surgery). The goal is to shrink the tumour, improve resection margins, and reduce local recurrence."}
{"query_id":"q110","question":"What follow-up is recommended after curative resection of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After curative resection, follow-up typically includes regular clinical consultations, CEA blood tests every three to six months for the first three years, CT scans every six to twelve months for the first three years, and colonoscopy at one year post-surgery. The schedule may vary by guideline and individual risk."}
{"query_id":"q111","question":"What is bowel cancer and how does it develop?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel cancer, also called colorectal cancer, develops from the inner lining of the colon or rectum. It usually begins as a small non-cancerous growth called a polyp that, over time, can develop into cancer. Most bowel cancers develop slowly over many years."}
{"query_id":"q112","question":"How is bowel cancer diagnosed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel cancer is diagnosed through a combination of tests including a colonoscopy to view the bowel lining and take biopsies, CT scan, blood tests including CEA level, and pathological examination of biopsy tissue. A flexible sigmoidoscopy or CT colonography may also be used."}
{"query_id":"q113","question":"What types of surgery are performed for bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Surgery for bowel cancer includes right hemicolectomy, left hemicolectomy, sigmoid colectomy, anterior resection, and abdominoperineal resection, depending on where the cancer is located. The goal is to remove the cancer along with a margin of healthy bowel and nearby lymph nodes. A stoma may be needed temporarily or permanently."}
{"query_id":"q114","question":"What does life look like after treatment for bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Life after bowel cancer treatment may involve adjusting to changes in bowel function, managing fatigue, attending regular follow-up appointments, and making lifestyle changes. Many people return to full activity and enjoy a good quality of life after treatment, though some experience lasting side effects."}
{"query_id":"q115","question":"What are the main risk factors for bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risk factors for bowel cancer include age over 50, family history, obesity, physical inactivity, a diet high in red and processed meat and low in fibre, alcohol consumption, smoking, type 2 diabetes, and a personal history of bowel polyps or inflammatory bowel disease."}
{"query_id":"q116","question":"What tests are used to diagnose bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel cancer diagnosis involves a colonoscopy as the primary diagnostic tool, with biopsy of suspicious areas. CT scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis is used for staging. Blood tests including full blood count and CEA, and an MRI for rectal tumours, complete the workup."}
{"query_id":"q117","question":"What are the different types of surgery available for bowel cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Depending on tumour location, surgery options include hemicolectomy (removal of part of the colon), sigmoid colectomy, anterior resection for upper rectal tumours, and abdominoperineal resection for low rectal tumours requiring permanent colostomy. Laparoscopic (keyhole) surgery is increasingly common and associated with faster recovery."}
{"query_id":"q118","question":"What support services are available for bowel cancer patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Support services include cancer care nurses, dietitians, social workers, counsellors, physiotherapists, and peer support groups. Cancer Council Australia provides information, telephone support lines, and local community support programs for people affected by bowel cancer."}
{"query_id":"q119","question":"How is colorectal cancer staged in clinical practice?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colorectal cancer is staged using the TNM system or the Dukes classification. Staging is based on imaging findings and confirmed pathologically after surgery. Stage determines prognosis and guides whether adjuvant treatment is needed after surgery."}
{"query_id":"q120","question":"What is the role of a multidisciplinary team in colorectal cancer care?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A multidisciplinary team (MDT) includes colorectal surgeons, oncologists, radiologists, pathologists, gastroenterologists, specialist nurses, and allied health professionals. The MDT reviews each patient's case to agree on an individualised treatment plan and coordinates care across specialties."}
{"query_id":"q121","question":"What adjuvant treatment is recommended after surgery for colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Adjuvant chemotherapy is recommended for stage III colon cancer and selected high-risk stage II patients. FOLFOX or CAPOX for six months are the standard regimens. Patients with dMMR/MSI-H tumours may not benefit from fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy alone."}
{"query_id":"q122","question":"What surveillance is recommended after colorectal cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Post-treatment surveillance includes regular clinical review, CEA monitoring every three to six months for three years, annual CT scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis for three years, and colonoscopy at one year. The frequency may be adjusted based on tumour stage and risk."}
{"query_id":"q123","question":"What is colorectal cancer and how is it classified?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colorectal cancer is cancer of the colon or rectum, the final parts of the digestive system. It is classified by location (colon vs rectal), stage (I to IV based on extent of spread), and tumour characteristics such as histology and molecular profile."}
{"query_id":"q124","question":"What are the warning symptoms of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Warning symptoms include a persistent change in bowel habits, blood in or on the stool, abdominal pain or bloating, unexplained weight loss, and unexplained fatigue or anaemia. Anyone experiencing these symptoms for more than a few weeks should be assessed by a doctor."}
{"query_id":"q125","question":"What treatment options are available for colorectal cancer patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Treatment depends on stage and tumour characteristics and may include surgery, chemotherapy, radiotherapy, targeted therapy, and immunotherapy. Most patients with non-metastatic disease are offered curative surgery, possibly combined with chemotherapy or radiotherapy. Metastatic disease is usually managed with systemic treatment."}
{"query_id":"q126","question":"What support is available for patients with colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Support includes clinical nurse specialists, Macmillan or Cancer Research UK resources, local support groups, psychological counselling, financial advice services, and online communities. Patients should be given information about these resources at diagnosis and throughout treatment."}
{"query_id":"q127","question":"What health inequalities exist in bowel cancer outcomes?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Health inequalities in bowel cancer include worse outcomes for people living in deprived areas, those from minority ethnic groups, people with learning disabilities, and older adults. These groups are less likely to be screened, diagnosed at an earlier stage, or receive guideline-recommended treatment."}
{"query_id":"q128","question":"How do bowel cancer outcomes differ for people with learning disabilities?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with learning disabilities are more likely to be diagnosed with bowel cancer at a later stage and have worse outcomes compared to the general population. Barriers include difficulty recognising or communicating symptoms, lower uptake of screening, and healthcare systems not always adapted to their needs."}
{"query_id":"q129","question":"What are the barriers to bowel cancer screening in vulnerable populations?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Barriers to bowel cancer screening include low health literacy, language barriers, distrust of healthcare services, physical or cognitive difficulties completing the test, lack of information in accessible formats, and social circumstances such as homelessness or unstable housing."}
{"query_id":"q130","question":"What changes are recommended to improve equity in bowel cancer care?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Recommendations include providing screening in accessible formats, training healthcare staff in working with people with learning disabilities, improving data collection on health inequalities, and developing targeted outreach to underserved groups to increase screening uptake and early detection."}
{"query_id":"q131","question":"How is colon cancer diagnosed according to current NCCN guidelines?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Diagnosis involves colonoscopy with biopsy to confirm cancer histology, CT scan of the chest, abdomen and pelvis for staging, CEA blood test, and pathological review including mismatch repair and RAS/BRAF testing. Endoscopic ultrasound or MRI may be used for local staging in selected cases."}
{"query_id":"q132","question":"What is the recommended treatment for stage II colon cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The primary treatment for stage II colon cancer is surgical resection. Adjuvant chemotherapy is generally not recommended for low-risk stage II but is considered for high-risk features such as T4 tumour, bowel obstruction or perforation, poorly differentiated histology, and positive or close margins."}
{"query_id":"q133","question":"What follow-up care is recommended after colon cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Follow-up includes clinical evaluation and CEA monitoring every three to six months for two years, then every six months for years three to five. CT imaging of chest and abdomen/pelvis annually for five years. Colonoscopy at one year post-surgery, then every three to five years if negative."}
{"query_id":"q134","question":"How does hereditary colorectal cancer influence treatment decisions?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients with hereditary syndromes such as Lynch syndrome may need more extensive surgery such as total colectomy rather than segmental resection to reduce the risk of new primary cancers. Immunotherapy may be particularly effective. Family members should be offered genetic counselling and early screening."}
{"query_id":"q135","question":"What is DPYD deficiency and which chemotherapy drugs does it affect?","language":"en","reference_answer":"DPYD deficiency is a reduction or absence of the enzyme dihydropyrimidine dehydrogenase, which is responsible for breaking down fluoropyrimidine drugs. Affected drugs include 5-fluorouracil (5-FU) and capecitabine. Patients with DPYD variants may accumulate toxic levels of these drugs at standard doses."}
{"query_id":"q136","question":"How should DPYD testing be performed before fluoropyrimidine chemotherapy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"DPYD testing involves genotyping for the most clinically significant DPYD variants (typically DPYD*2A, c.2846A>T, c.1679T>G, and HapB3) from a blood sample. Testing should ideally be completed before starting fluoropyrimidine-based chemotherapy so that results can guide dosing decisions."}
{"query_id":"q137","question":"What dose adjustments are recommended for patients with DPYD variants?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients with heterozygous DPYD variants generally receive a 25% to 50% dose reduction of fluoropyrimidine drugs, depending on the specific variant and its activity score. Homozygous or compound heterozygous patients with no DPYD activity should avoid fluoropyrimidine drugs entirely if alternative regimens are available."}
{"query_id":"q138","question":"Which patients should undergo DPYD testing before chemotherapy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"DPYD testing is recommended for all patients planned to receive fluoropyrimidine-based chemotherapy, including 5-FU, capecitabine, or tegafur-containing regimens. Universal pre-treatment testing is now recommended in many European countries and increasingly adopted in other settings."}
{"query_id":"q139","question":"What are NCCN recommendations for average-risk colorectal cancer screening?","language":"en","reference_answer":"For average-risk adults, NCCN recommends beginning colorectal cancer screening at age 45. Acceptable screening options include annual FIT or gFOBT, stool DNA test every one to three years, CT colonography every five years, flexible sigmoidoscopy every five years, or colonoscopy every ten years."}
{"query_id":"q140","question":"How does family history of colorectal cancer affect screening recommendations?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a first-degree relative diagnosed with colorectal cancer or advanced adenoma should begin screening at age 40 or 10 years before the youngest affected relative's diagnosis, whichever comes first. Colonoscopy every five years is typically recommended in this group rather than stool-based tests."}
{"query_id":"q141","question":"What colorectal cancer screening is recommended for people with Lynch syndrome?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with Lynch syndrome should begin colonoscopy screening at age 20 to 25, or five to ten years before the earliest colorectal cancer in the family, whichever comes first. Colonoscopy should be repeated every one to two years due to the increased risk and faster polyp progression in this syndrome."}
{"query_id":"q142","question":"How do colonoscopy and stool tests compare for colorectal cancer screening?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Colonoscopy allows direct visualisation of the entire colon, biopsy or removal of polyps in the same procedure, and is recommended every ten years if negative. Stool tests are less invasive and can be done at home but must be done more frequently and a positive result requires follow-up colonoscopy. Both approaches reduce colorectal cancer mortality."}
{"query_id":"q143","question":"How is rectal cancer staged and what investigations are needed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Rectal cancer staging requires MRI of the pelvis to assess tumour depth, relationship to the mesorectal fascia, and lymph node involvement. CT scan of the chest, abdomen, and pelvis stages systemic disease. Endorectal ultrasound may assess early tumours. Biopsy confirms histology and molecular testing guides systemic treatment."}
{"query_id":"q144","question":"What is total neoadjuvant therapy for rectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Total neoadjuvant therapy (TNT) delivers all planned chemotherapy and radiotherapy before surgery rather than splitting treatment around the operation. This approach may achieve higher rates of complete tumour response, improve tolerability, and potentially allow organ preservation in some patients with rectal cancer."}
{"query_id":"q145","question":"When is a permanent colostomy required for rectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A permanent colostomy is typically required for low rectal cancers where it is not technically possible to join the bowel after removing the tumour, or when the anal sphincter must be removed as part of the operation (abdominoperineal resection). It may also be needed if complications prevent reversal of a temporary stoma."}
{"query_id":"q146","question":"What follow-up is recommended after treatment for rectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After rectal cancer treatment, follow-up includes regular clinical assessments, CEA monitoring, CT imaging of chest and abdomen/pelvis annually for up to five years, and endoscopic surveillance. Patients who have had a sphincter-preserving resection may need specific assessment for bowel dysfunction such as LARS."}
{"query_id":"q147","question":"What is a colostomy and how does it function?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A colostomy is a surgical opening in the abdomen where part of the colon is brought to the skin surface to create a stoma. Stools pass out through the stoma into a bag worn on the abdomen instead of through the rectum and anus. A colostomy may be temporary or permanent."}
{"query_id":"q148","question":"How should a colostomy bag be emptied and changed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A colostomy bag should be emptied when it is one-third to one-half full by opening the clip at the bottom. The bag is changed every two to four days by gently peeling off the flange, cleaning the stoma and skin, drying well, and attaching a fresh pouch. Supplies and technique should be taught by a stoma nurse."}
{"query_id":"q149","question":"What dietary advice is given to people with a new colostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a new colostomy should eat regular balanced meals, drink at least two litres of fluid daily, chew food thoroughly, and eat slowly. Initially they may be advised to avoid foods that cause excess wind or loose stools. Foods and their effects vary between individuals."}
{"query_id":"q150","question":"When can patients with a colostomy return to normal daily activities?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Most patients can gradually return to normal activities including work, exercise, swimming, and social activities after a colostomy, though the timeline depends on recovery from surgery. Specific guidance on activity restrictions and return to exercise should be given by the surgical team and stoma nurse."}
{"query_id":"q151","question":"What is a right hemicolectomy and when is it performed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A right hemicolectomy is surgery to remove the right side of the colon, including the ascending colon and sometimes the terminal ileum. It is performed for cancers or large polyps located in the right colon (caecum, ascending colon, or hepatic flexure). The remaining bowel is joined together."}
{"query_id":"q152","question":"What should patients expect during recovery from a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Recovery from a right hemicolectomy typically involves a hospital stay of three to seven days, with gradual return to eating and drinking. Patients may experience some temporary bowel changes such as looser stools. Pain is managed with medications, and patients are encouraged to mobilise early. Full recovery usually takes four to six weeks."}
{"query_id":"q153","question":"What dietary advice should patients follow after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After right hemicolectomy, patients should start with fluids and light foods, gradually introducing a normal diet. They may have looser stools initially and should increase fluid intake. Some patients may need to limit high-fibre foods initially. A dietitian can provide tailored advice."}
{"query_id":"q154","question":"What symptoms after a right hemicolectomy should prompt urgent medical attention?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should seek urgent medical attention for severe abdominal pain, high fever, inability to eat or drink, vomiting, wound that becomes red, swollen, or has discharge, and no bowel movement within three to four days of discharge. These could indicate serious complications."}
{"query_id":"q155","question":"How long is the typical hospital stay after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The typical hospital stay after a right hemicolectomy is three to seven days, though this can vary depending on whether laparoscopic or open surgery was performed, how quickly bowel function returns, and whether any complications occur. Enhanced recovery protocols aim to shorten hospital stays safely."}
{"query_id":"q156","question":"How should patients care for their wound at home after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Wounds should be kept clean and dry. Patients with clips or sutures are usually given instructions on when to have them removed. Any redness, swelling, discharge, or opening of the wound should be reported to the GP or surgical team. Abdominal binders may help if recommended."}
{"query_id":"q157","question":"What activities should be avoided after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After a right hemicolectomy, patients should avoid heavy lifting, strenuous exercise, and driving until cleared by their surgical team, usually around four to six weeks after open surgery. Light walking is encouraged from the day after surgery to aid recovery and reduce the risk of blood clots."}
{"query_id":"q158","question":"When can patients return to work after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Return to work depends on the type of work and how recovery progresses. For desk-based work, return may be possible after two to four weeks. For physically demanding jobs, patients may need six to twelve weeks. Patients should discuss timing with their surgical team and employer."}
{"query_id":"q159","question":"What treatments are available for low anterior resection syndrome?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Treatment options for LARS include dietary modification, loperamide or other antidiarrhoeals, pelvic floor physiotherapy, biofeedback therapy, transanal irrigation, and in severe cases sacral nerve stimulation. A stepped care approach is usually taken, starting with conservative measures."}
{"query_id":"q160","question":"How does bowel retraining help manage LARS symptoms?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel retraining teaches patients to establish a regular bowel routine and recognise and respond appropriately to bowel urges. Techniques include scheduled toileting, responding promptly to urge, avoiding straining, and using positions that aid complete emptying. Physiotherapy guidance supports this process."}
{"query_id":"q161","question":"What dietary changes can help manage symptoms of LARS?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Dietary changes for LARS may include eating smaller and more frequent meals, avoiding foods that trigger urgency or loose stools, ensuring adequate fibre intake, drinking plenty of fluids, and identifying personal food triggers. A dietitian experienced in bowel dysfunction can provide tailored guidance."}
{"query_id":"q162","question":"What is the impact of LARS on quality of life and when should patients seek help?","language":"en","reference_answer":"LARS can significantly affect quality of life including social activities, work, relationships, sleep, and emotional wellbeing. Patients should seek help if bowel symptoms are affecting daily life, as effective treatments are available. Routine assessment of LARS symptoms should be part of post-treatment follow-up."}
{"query_id":"q163","question":"What is a left hemicolectomy and which part of the bowel is removed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A left hemicolectomy removes the left side of the colon, which includes the descending colon and sometimes the splenic flexure. It is performed for cancers in the left colon. The remaining ends of the bowel are joined together in a procedure called an anastomosis."}
{"query_id":"q164","question":"What is the typical recovery timeline after a left hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Recovery after a left hemicolectomy involves a hospital stay of four to seven days. Bowel function returns gradually and patients are encouraged to mobilise early. Patients can usually return to light activities within two to three weeks and full activity within four to six weeks, depending on whether keyhole or open surgery was used."}
{"query_id":"q165","question":"What dietary advice should be followed after a left hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After a left hemicolectomy, patients should start with fluids and soft foods, gradually returning to a normal diet. Fluid intake should be maintained. Some patients experience looser stools, so avoiding very high fibre foods initially may help. A dietitian can advise on longer-term dietary management."}
{"query_id":"q166","question":"What signs of complications should patients watch for after a left hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Signs of complications include severe abdominal pain, high fever, wound discharge or breakdown, inability to eat or drink, and no bowel movement after several days of discharge. An anastomotic leak, though uncommon, can present as sudden worsening pain and fever and requires urgent medical assessment."}
{"query_id":"q167","question":"What preparation is required before a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Before a right hemicolectomy, patients typically attend pre-assessment clinics, have blood tests and scans, are assessed for fitness for surgery, and may be given bowel preparation or dietary instructions. They will be advised on stopping certain medications such as blood thinners and given information about enhanced recovery."}
{"query_id":"q168","question":"How is pain managed after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Pain after a right hemicolectomy is managed with a combination of regular paracetamol, anti-inflammatories if suitable, opioid analgesics for more severe pain, and epidural or patient-controlled analgesia in the immediate post-operative period. The pain team supports patients with complex needs."}
{"query_id":"q169","question":"What bowel changes can occur after a right hemicolectomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Removing the right colon affects water absorption, which may lead to looser, more frequent bowel movements initially. Most patients find their bowel function gradually normalises over weeks to months. Some patients may have permanently looser stools. Adequate hydration is important."}
{"query_id":"q170","question":"What are the long-term outcomes after a right hemicolectomy for cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Long-term outcomes depend primarily on the stage of cancer. Most patients recover well with good bowel function. Regular follow-up is needed to detect recurrence. Adjuvant chemotherapy may be offered for stage III tumours. Overall, surgical outcomes for right colon cancer are generally good with curative intent surgery."}
{"query_id":"q171","question":"What does NICE recommend for the diagnosis of colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"NICE recommends urgent referral for colonoscopy for people presenting with symptoms suggesting colorectal cancer. CT colonography is an alternative for those unable to tolerate colonoscopy. Faecal immunochemical testing (FIT) may be used as a triage tool. All suspicious lesions should be biopsied and assessed pathologically."}
{"query_id":"q172","question":"What does NICE guidance say about surgery for colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"NICE recommends surgery as the primary treatment for colorectal cancer with curative intent. Laparoscopic surgery is recommended over open surgery when suitable, as it is associated with faster recovery and similar long-term outcomes. Pre-operative assessment and multidisciplinary team discussion should guide the surgical approach."}
{"query_id":"q173","question":"What are NICE recommendations on adjuvant chemotherapy for colorectal cancer?","language":"en","reference_answer":"NICE recommends adjuvant chemotherapy for stage III colon cancer using FOLFOX or CAPOX regimens. For rectal cancer, preoperative chemoradiation is recommended for locally advanced tumours. High-risk stage II colon cancer should be discussed at MDT for consideration of adjuvant chemotherapy."}
{"query_id":"q174","question":"What does NICE say about follow-up after colorectal cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"NICE recommends structured follow-up for people who have had curative treatment for colorectal cancer, including regular CEA measurements, CT surveillance, and colonoscopy. The frequency and duration of follow-up should be based on the individual's risk and should be supported by a key worker."}
{"query_id":"q175","question":"What is stratified follow-up for colorectal cancer and why is it used?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Stratified follow-up matches the intensity of post-treatment surveillance to the individual patient's risk of recurrence. Low-risk patients may be supported with self-management and remote monitoring, while high-risk patients receive more frequent clinical contact. This approach aims to make better use of clinical resources while maintaining patient safety."}
{"query_id":"q176","question":"Which colorectal cancer patients are eligible for self-managed or remote follow-up?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients with low-risk colorectal cancer, typically those with stage I or low-risk stage II disease after curative surgery, may be eligible for a more remote or self-managed follow-up pathway. This requires good health literacy, a clear safety-netting plan, and agreed criteria for re-referral."}
{"query_id":"q177","question":"What symptoms should prompt urgent re-referral after colorectal cancer treatment?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Symptoms warranting urgent re-referral include rectal bleeding, unexplained weight loss, new or worsening abdominal pain, change in bowel habit, rising CEA levels, new symptoms suggesting distant metastasis such as persistent cough or bone pain, and any other concerns about possible recurrence."}
{"query_id":"q178","question":"How frequently should CEA be checked during colorectal cancer follow-up?","language":"en","reference_answer":"CEA should be measured every three to six months for the first three years after curative treatment for colorectal cancer. A rising CEA level can indicate recurrence before imaging detects it and should prompt further investigation and review."}
{"query_id":"q179","question":"What activity levels are safe when discharged home after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After discharge from colorectal surgery, patients are encouraged to mobilise gradually, walking a little more each day. Climbing stairs is usually fine. Heavy lifting, driving, and strenuous activity should be avoided until cleared by the surgical team, typically at four to six weeks."}
{"query_id":"q180","question":"How should patients care for their wound at home after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should keep the wound clean and dry. Showering is usually permitted. Wound closures such as clips or sutures are removed in the community at the appropriate time. Any redness, swelling, discharge, or unusual pain around the wound should be reported to the GP or surgical team."}
{"query_id":"q181","question":"What dietary advice should patients follow on discharge after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"On discharge, patients are advised to eat small regular meals, increase portion sizes as appetite returns, stay well hydrated, and avoid very fatty, spicy, or high-fibre foods initially. They should gradually return to their normal diet and contact a dietitian if they have ongoing concerns."}
{"query_id":"q182","question":"What symptoms after colorectal surgery should prompt an emergency call?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should call 999 or go to the emergency department if they develop severe or worsening abdominal pain, high fever (above 38 degrees), inability to keep any fluids down, signs of wound breakdown, heavy bleeding, or sudden deterioration in general condition."}
{"query_id":"q183","question":"What is an anterior resection and what does the surgery involve?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Anterior resection is surgery to remove the upper part of the rectum and sometimes part of the sigmoid colon. The two ends of the bowel are then joined together, usually with a circular stapling device. A temporary loop ileostomy is often formed to protect the join while it heals."}
{"query_id":"q184","question":"How should patients manage bowel changes after an anterior resection?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Bowel changes after anterior resection, sometimes called anterior resection syndrome, include frequency, urgency, and difficulty emptying the bowel. Management includes dietary modification, pelvic floor exercises, loperamide, biofeedback, and transanal irrigation. Specialist physiotherapy and nurse support can help."}
{"query_id":"q185","question":"What activity restrictions should patients follow after anterior resection surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should avoid heavy lifting, strenuous activity, and driving for at least four to six weeks after anterior resection. Light walking is encouraged from early in the recovery period. The surgical team will advise when it is safe to resume specific activities based on individual recovery."}
{"query_id":"q186","question":"What complications should be watched for after anterior resection surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Complications after anterior resection include anastomotic leak (bowel join breaking down), pelvic sepsis, bleeding, wound infection, and urinary retention. If a patient has a stoma, any stoma complications such as skin problems or retraction should also be reported. Anastomotic leak is the most serious early complication."}
{"query_id":"q187","question":"What happens during stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"During stoma reversal surgery, the stoma is closed and the two ends of the bowel are joined back together. For a loop ileostomy, this involves closing the opening in the loop or disconnecting and rejoining the ends. The operation is usually shorter and less complex than the original surgery and may be done as keyhole surgery."}
{"query_id":"q188","question":"How should patients prepare for stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Preparation for stoma reversal may include endoscopic assessment of the bowel join, bowel preparation, pre-operative blood tests and scans, and assessment of anal sphincter function. Patients should be fit enough for surgery and have completed any planned chemotherapy or radiotherapy before the reversal."}
{"query_id":"q189","question":"What are the risks associated with stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Risks include anastomotic leak, wound infection, bleeding, bowel obstruction, and failure of reversal requiring a permanent stoma. There is also a risk of long-term bowel dysfunction such as frequency, urgency, and difficulty with continence after reversal."}
{"query_id":"q190","question":"What can patients expect during recovery from stoma reversal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After stoma reversal, patients typically stay in hospital for three to five days. Bowel function resumes but may be unpredictable initially, with frequent loose stools or urgency. This usually improves over weeks to months. Pelvic floor exercises and dietary adjustments support recovery."}
{"query_id":"q191","question":"What should patients expect when going home after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Going home after colorectal surgery involves managing pain with prescribed medications, making dietary adjustments, caring for the wound, gradually increasing activity, and attending follow-up appointments. Written information and contact numbers for the surgical team or nurse should be provided on discharge."}
{"query_id":"q192","question":"What medications should patients take on discharge after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"On discharge, patients are usually prescribed regular analgesia such as paracetamol and anti-inflammatories, laxatives to prevent constipation, iron supplements if needed for anaemia, blood thinning injections to prevent DVT, and any regular medications they were on before surgery."}
{"query_id":"q193","question":"What eating and drinking advice should patients follow after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After colorectal surgery, patients should eat small regular meals and increase intake gradually. Fluids are important to stay hydrated and support bowel function. Initially, soft and easily digestible foods are recommended. Alcohol should be avoided while on strong painkillers."}
{"query_id":"q194","question":"When will patients have their follow-up appointments after colorectal surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Follow-up appointments are usually arranged before discharge. A wound check or clip removal may occur within the first two weeks. A surgical clinic review typically happens at four to six weeks. Oncology review and tumour board discussion may follow once pathology results are available."}
{"query_id":"q195","question":"How do you empty and change a colostomy pouch?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A colostomy pouch is emptied by opening the tail closure and draining contents into the toilet. To change the pouch, remove the old bag by peeling the adhesive from the skin, clean the stoma and surrounding skin with warm water and pat dry, measure the stoma opening, cut the new flange to fit, and press firmly onto clean dry skin."}
{"query_id":"q196","question":"What dietary changes are important when living with a colostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a colostomy should eat a balanced diet, drink plenty of fluids, chew food well, and eat regular meals. Certain foods such as beans, cabbage, fizzy drinks, and onions may increase gas. High-fibre foods may produce a bulkier output. Individual responses vary and keeping a food diary can help identify triggers."}
{"query_id":"q197","question":"Can people with a colostomy exercise or go swimming?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Yes, people with a colostomy can exercise and swim. For swimming, the pouch should be empty and secured, and a waterproof cover or swimwear designed for ostomy wearers can provide extra security. Exercise is encouraged for general health and there are no specific activities that a colostomy prevents."}
{"query_id":"q198","question":"How can people adjust emotionally to living with a colostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Emotional adjustment to a colostomy takes time and is different for everyone. Support from a stoma care nurse, counsellor, or peer support group can help. Many people successfully adjust and return to full, active lives. Online communities and organisations such as UOAA provide valuable information and peer connection."}
{"query_id":"q199","question":"What is a J-pouch and how does it work?","language":"en","reference_answer":"A J-pouch, or ileal pouch-anal anastomosis (IPAA), is a surgically created internal reservoir made from the end of the small intestine. After removal of the entire colon and rectum, the J-pouch serves as a replacement rectum, allowing the person to pass stools naturally through the anus without a permanent stoma."}
{"query_id":"q200","question":"What dietary restrictions should be followed after J-pouch surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"After J-pouch surgery, patients should eat small and frequent meals, chew food thoroughly, stay well hydrated, and monitor foods that increase stool frequency or cause gas. High-fibre and high-fat foods, as well as spicy food and alcohol, may worsen symptoms initially. A dietitian can help optimise nutrition."}
{"query_id":"q201","question":"How many bowel movements per day is normal for someone with a J-pouch?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with a J-pouch typically have four to eight bowel movements per day, which is more than the normal one to two but far fewer than with an ileostomy. Output often decreases over the first one to two years as the pouch adapts and stretches. Frequency and consistency can be influenced by diet and medications."}
{"query_id":"q202","question":"What long-term complications can occur with a J-pouch and how are they managed?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Long-term J-pouch complications include pouchitis (inflammation of the pouch), cuffitis, pouch failure requiring permanent ileostomy, and bowel obstruction. Pouchitis is the most common complication and is treated with antibiotics. Ongoing surveillance of the pouch is recommended."}
{"query_id":"q203","question":"How should an ileostomy stoma be cared for?","language":"en","reference_answer":"An ileostomy stoma should be kept clean by washing with warm water and patting dry. The stoma and surrounding skin should be inspected at each pouch change for signs of skin irritation, bleeding, or stoma changes. The pouch should be fitted carefully to protect the skin from contact with liquid effluent."}
{"query_id":"q204","question":"What foods should people with an ileostomy avoid or limit?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with an ileostomy should be cautious with high-fibre foods such as raw vegetables, nuts, seeds, and dried fruit as these may cause blockages. Some individuals find that certain foods increase output or cause gas. Foods are reintroduced gradually and individual tolerance varies."}
{"query_id":"q205","question":"How can dehydration be managed and prevented with an ileostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"People with an ileostomy are at higher risk of dehydration because the colon, which absorbs water, has been bypassed. Patients should drink at least two litres of fluid per day, increase intake in hot weather or during exercise, replace electrolytes (especially sodium and potassium), and recognise signs of dehydration such as dark urine, thirst, and fatigue."}
{"query_id":"q206","question":"How can living with an ileostomy affect intimacy and relationships?","language":"en","reference_answer":"An ileostomy can affect body image, confidence, and intimacy. Many people worry about their partner's reaction or about the pouch during physical contact. Specialist nurses, counsellors, and peer support can help. Most people can enjoy fulfilling intimate relationships with an ileostomy, and openly discussing concerns with a partner is encouraged."}
{"query_id":"q207","question":"What are the different types of ostomy?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The main types of ostomy are colostomy (formed from the colon), ileostomy (formed from the small intestine), and urostomy (formed from the urinary tract, usually after bladder removal). Each type produces different output: colostomy produces formed or semi-formed stool, ileostomy produces liquid to porridge-like output, and urostomy produces urine."}
{"query_id":"q208","question":"How should a person choose the right ostomy pouching system?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Choosing an ostomy pouching system should be done in consultation with a stoma care nurse. Factors include stoma type and output consistency, skin condition, body contour, lifestyle, and personal preference. One-piece and two-piece systems are available, as well as closed, drainable, and urostomy pouches. Samples can be tried before committing to a product."}
{"query_id":"q209","question":"How should the skin around an ostomy stoma be cared for?","language":"en","reference_answer":"The skin around the stoma (peristomal skin) should be cleaned gently at each pouch change, checked for redness, rash, or erosion, and protected with appropriate barrier products. The pouch should fit the stoma precisely to avoid skin contact with effluent. Any persistent skin problems should be assessed by a stoma nurse."}
{"query_id":"q210","question":"When can people with an ostomy return to work and daily activities?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Most people with an ostomy can return to work and full daily activities after recovery from surgery, usually within four to eight weeks depending on the type of work. Ostomy should not prevent participation in sports, travel, socialising, or work. A stoma nurse can advise on managing specific activities."}
{"query_id":"q211","question":"What should new ostomy patients expect in the first weeks after surgery?","language":"en","reference_answer":"In the first weeks, new ostomy patients are learning to manage their pouching system with support from a stoma nurse. The stoma may be swollen initially and will shrink over four to eight weeks. Output will vary and stabilise over time. Emotions may fluctuate and this is normal. Practical support and information are key at this stage."}
{"query_id":"q212","question":"How can common ostomy problems such as leaks and skin irritation be resolved?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Leaks are often caused by a poor fit between the pouch and stoma. Measuring the stoma and cutting the flange accurately, ensuring skin is clean and dry before application, and using barrier rings or paste can help. Skin irritation usually improves when the cause is identified and corrected. A stoma nurse can troubleshoot persistent problems."}
{"query_id":"q213","question":"When should a new ostomy patient contact their stoma nurse?","language":"en","reference_answer":"New ostomy patients should contact their stoma nurse if they experience persistent leaks or skin problems, changes in the stoma appearance such as colour change, prolapse or retraction, signs of blockage such as no output with cramping, or any concerns they are unable to manage independently."}
{"query_id":"q214","question":"What resources are available to support new ostomy patients?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Resources include specialist stoma care nurses, home delivery services for pouching supplies, patient organisations such as UOAA and the Colostomy Association, online communities and forums, printed patient education materials, and peer visitor programmes where people can speak with experienced ostomy patients."}
{"query_id":"q215","question":"How can peristomal skin breakdown be prevented?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Prevention of peristomal skin breakdown involves ensuring the pouching system fits correctly so effluent does not contact the skin, changing the pouch before it leaks, using skin barrier products, cleaning and thoroughly drying the peristomal skin at each change, and addressing any allergic reactions to adhesives promptly."}
{"query_id":"q216","question":"What skin protection products are recommended for ostomy care?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Products recommended for peristomal skin protection include skin barrier wipes or sprays, barrier rings or seals, convex flanges for retracted stomas, ostomy paste to fill contour irregularities, and medical adhesive removers to protect the skin during pouch removal. A stoma nurse can recommend appropriate products for individual needs."}
{"query_id":"q217","question":"How should peristomal skin irritation or rash be treated?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Treatment of peristomal skin irritation depends on the cause. Mechanical damage from frequent pouch changes or adhesive trauma is treated by extending wear time and using adhesive remover. Chemical irritation from effluent contact is treated by improving the pouch fit. Fungal infections are treated with antifungal powder. Allergic reactions require identifying and changing the offending product."}
{"query_id":"q218","question":"When should a patient seek professional help for an ostomy skin problem?","language":"en","reference_answer":"Patients should seek professional help from a stoma nurse or doctor if peristomal skin problems do not improve within a few days, if the skin is broken, bleeding, or has a rash spreading beyond the peristomal area, if there is suspected fungal or bacterial infection, or if pouching problems are causing repeated leaks affecting quality of life."}
